Unsupervised Learning: Trade&Ahead Project¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

The stock market has consistently proven to be a good place to invest in and save for the future. There are a lot of compelling reasons to invest in stocks. It can help in fighting inflation, create wealth, and also provides some tax benefits. Good steady returns on investments over a long period of time can also grow a lot more than seems possible. Also, thanks to the power of compound interest, the earlier one starts investing, the larger the corpus one can have for retirement. Overall, investing in stocks can help meet life's financial aspirations.

It is important to maintain a diversified portfolio when investing in stocks in order to maximise earnings under any market condition. Having a diversified portfolio tends to yield higher returns and face lower risk by tempering potential losses when the market is down. It is often easy to get lost in a sea of financial metrics to analyze while determining the worth of a stock, and doing the same for a multitude of stocks to identify the right picks for an individual can be a tedious task. By doing a cluster analysis, one can identify stocks that exhibit similar characteristics and ones which exhibit minimum correlation. This will help investors better analyze stocks across different market segments and help protect against risks that could make the portfolio vulnerable to losses.

Objective¶

Trade&Ahead is a financial consultancy firm who provide their customers with personalized investment strategies. They have hired you as a Data Scientist and provided you with data comprising stock price and some financial indicators for a few companies listed under the New York Stock Exchange. They have assigned you the tasks of analyzing the data, grouping the stocks based on the attributes provided, and sharing insights about the characteristics of each group.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Ticker Symbol: An abbreviation used to uniquely identify publicly traded shares of a particular stock on a particular stock market
  • Company: Name of the company
  • GICS Sector: The specific economic sector assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • GICS Sub Industry: The specific sub-industry group assigned to a company by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS) that best defines its business operations
  • Current Price: Current stock price in dollars
  • Price Change: Percentage change in the stock price in 13 weeks
  • Volatility: Standard deviation of the stock price over the past 13 weeks
  • ROE: A measure of financial performance calculated by dividing net income by shareholders' equity (shareholders' equity is equal to a company's assets minus its debt)
  • Cash Ratio: The ratio of a company's total reserves of cash and cash equivalents to its total current liabilities
  • Net Cash Flow: The difference between a company's cash inflows and outflows (in dollars)
  • Net Income: Revenues minus expenses, interest, and taxes (in dollars)
  • Earnings Per Share: Company's net profit divided by the number of common shares it has outstanding (in dollars)
  • Estimated Shares Outstanding: Company's stock currently held by all its shareholders
  • P/E Ratio: Ratio of the company's current stock price to the earnings per share
  • P/B Ratio: Ratio of the company's stock price per share by its book value per share (book value of a company is the net difference between that company's total assets and total liabilities)

def histogram_boxplot(df, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=df, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=df, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        df[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )
In [12]:
def labeled_barplot(df, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(df[feature])  # length of the column
    count = df[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=df,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=df[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )

    plt.show()

Univariate Analyses of All Variables¶

  • Many of the variables, like Current Price, Volatility, ROE, Cash Ratio, Estimated Shares Outstanding and P/E Ratio are heavily skewed to the right.
  • Other variables like Price Change, Net Cash Flow, Net Income, Earnings Per Share and P/B Ratio have a more normally distributed pattern, all centering more or less around 0.
  • The top 5 GICS sectors are industrials, financials, health care, consumer discretionary and information technology. The smallest sectors are telecommunication services, consumer staples and materials.
  • In terms of the GICS sub industry, the top ones include oil and gas exploration and production, followed by REITs, industrial conglomerates electric ultities and internet software and services.

Correlation¶

  • There does not appear to be any strong correlation between any of the variables, but earnings per share, net income and estimated shares outstanding have some positive correlation with one another.
  • There are some negative correlation between net income and variables like volatility and ROE. Price change and earnings per share are also somewhat negatively correlated with volatility.

K-means Clustering¶

Checking Elbow Plot¶

  • The K-value, judging from the first graph below, seems to be at around 6.
  • The distortion score elbow for means clustering graph confirms that the K-value is indeed 6, with a score of 2211.520.
In [36]:
k_means_df = subset_scaled_df.copy()
In [37]:
clusters = range(1, 15)
meanDistortions = []

for k in clusters:
    model = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1)
    model.fit(subset_scaled_df)
    prediction = model.predict(k_means_df)
    distortion = (
        sum(np.min(cdist(k_means_df, model.cluster_centers_, "euclidean"), axis=1))
        / k_means_df.shape[0]
    )

    meanDistortions.append(distortion)

    print("Number of Clusters:", k, "\tAverage Distortion:", distortion)

plt.plot(clusters, meanDistortions, "bx-")
plt.xlabel("k")
plt.ylabel("Average Distortion")
plt.title("Selecting k with the Elbow Method", fontsize=20)
plt.show()

Checking the Silhouette Scores¶

  • The appropriate K-value seems to be 3, as it has the highest silhouette score.
  • However, when it comes to the K-means clustering, the K-value is 2 instead with a score of 0.440.
In [39]:
sil_score = []
cluster_list = range(2, 15)
for n_clusters in cluster_list:
    clusterer = KMeans(n_clusters=n_clusters, random_state=1)
    preds = clusterer.fit_predict((subset_scaled_df))
    score = silhouette_score(k_means_df, preds)
    sil_score.append(score)
    print("For n_clusters = {}, the silhouette score is {})".format(n_clusters, score))

Creating Final Model¶

  • I chose the K-value of 2 because it has a decent silhouette score and it is in accordance to the silhouette score plot. While the K-value of 3 could be another good choice, I want to keep the model fairly simple and easy to be interpreted.

Insights Based on the Cluster Profiling¶

  • Cluster 0:
    • The average current prices are very low, with several outliers being low to moderate and one being extremely high.
    • The price changes are moderate, with some outliers at low and very high.
    • The volatility is overall low, although some are moderate.
    • The ROEs are extremely low but there are some that are relatively high.
    • The cash ratios are low with a lot of outliers in the moderate and high ranges.
    • The net cash flow is mostly at 0.0, with several lows and highs.
    • Both the net income and earnings per share are moderate, with some being high.
    • The estimated shares outstanding sits in the lower end but there are outliers that scatter across the high and moderate range.
    • The P/E ratios are very low and there are some that are a bit higher (still in the low range).
    • The P/B ratios are moderate, with several outliers on both ends, but there are more in the lower end.
  • Cluster 1:
    • The current prices are extremely low as well, but lower than those in Cluster 0.
    • The price changes are moderately low with some outliers being very low.
    • There is more volatility in this cluster as it is moderately high.
    • Both the ROEs and cash ratios are also very low.
    • The net cash flow for this cluster is more or less similar to that in Cluster 0 (moderate), though with less outliers.
    • The net income and earnings per share are also moderate, though a bit lower than those of Cluster 0. They have outliers in the low range.
    • The estimated shares outstanding is very low with fewer outliers that can be found in the moderate range.
    • The P/E ratios are higher than that of Cluster 0, with many outliers spreading towards the high end.
    • The P/B ratios are moderate, with very few outliers that are not too far from the majority.

Hierarchical Clustering¶

Computing Cophenetic Correlation¶

  • The manhattan distance cannot be used here and the chebyshev distance cannot work with the centroid, median and ward methods.
  • Using Euclidean distance and average linkage results in the highest correlation of about 0.9423.
In [51]:
hc_df = subset_scaled_df.copy()
In [52]:
distance_metrics = ['euclidean', 'manhattan', 'chebyshev']
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted', 'centroid', 'median', 'ward']

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for dm in distance_metrics:
    for lm in linkage_methods:
        try:
            Z = linkage(hc_df, metric=dm, method=lm)
            c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
            print(
                "Cophenetic correlation for {} distance and {} linkage is {}.".format(
                    dm.capitalize(), lm, c
                )
            )
            if high_cophenet_corr < c:
                high_cophenet_corr = c
                high_dm_lm[0] = dm
                high_dm_lm[1] = lm
        except ValueError:
            print("Skipping {} distance metric for {} linkage method.".format(dm, lm))

print('*'*100)
print(
    "Highest cophenetic correlation is {}, which is obtained with {} distance and {} linkage.".format(
        high_cophenet_corr, high_dm_lm[0].capitalize(), high_dm_lm[1]
    )
)

Looking at Linkage Methods Using Euclidean Distance Only¶

  • Again, the average linkage method has the best correlation. Using the single and centroid linkage is decent too.
  • The worst method here is ward linkage as it results in the lowest correlation.
In [53]:
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted', 'centroid', 'median', 'ward']

high_cophenet_corr = 0
high_dm_lm = [0, 0]

for lm in linkage_methods:
    try:
        Z = linkage(hc_df, metric="euclidean", method=lm)
        c, coph_dists = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
        print("Cophenetic correlation for {} linkage is {}.".format(lm, c))
        if high_cophenet_corr < c:
            high_cophenet_corr = c
            high_dm_lm[0] = "euclidean"
            high_dm_lm[1] = lm
    except NotImplementedError:
        print("Skipping {} linkage method.".format(lm))

print('*'*100)
print(
    "Highest cophenetic correlation is {}, which is obtained with {} linkage.".format(
        high_cophenet_corr, high_dm_lm[1]
    )
)

In [54]:
linkage_methods = ['single', 'complete', 'average', 'weighted', 'centroid', 'median', 'ward']

compare_cols = ["Linkage", "Cophenetic Coefficient"]
compare = []

fig, axs = plt.subplots(len(linkage_methods), 1, figsize=(15, 30))

for i, method in enumerate(linkage_methods):
    Z = linkage(hc_df, metric="euclidean", method=method)

    dendrogram(Z, ax=axs[i])
    axs[i].set_title(f"Dendrogram ({method.capitalize()} Linkage)")

    coph_corr, coph_dist = cophenet(Z, pdist(hc_df))
    axs[i].annotate(
        f"Cophenetic\nCorrelation\n{coph_corr:0.2f}",
        (0.80, 0.80),
        xycoords="axes fraction",
    )

    compare.append([method, coph_corr])

K-means vs. Hierarchical Clustering¶

  • The K-means clustering, using the K-value of 2, results in 307 observations listed in Cluster 0 and 33 others in Cluster 1. Meanwhile, the hierarchical clustering results in having 339 observations in Cluster 0 and only 1 observation in Cluster 1. I tried increasing the number of clusters for the hierarchical clustering up to 6, but the result was that for the rest of its clusters, only 1 or 2 companies would be listed under those.
  • This shows that the hierarchical clustering is very flawed and highly imbalanced compared to the K-means clustering. Thus, it is easier to interpret the data using the K-means clustering because at least there are more companies to analyze and compare.
  • The extreme imbalance in the hierarchical clustering could mean that the clusters are not well-separated so we cannot see any meaningful pattern in the data.
  • Both techniques took a fairly short time to execute. The difference in run time for each is almost unnoticeable.
  • As a result, the K-means clustering is the chosen model.

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

  • As discussed above, using the K-means clustering method is more efficient than using the hierarchical one because it is more balanced and offers better indications about the different types of stocks that each company has.
  • Companies that are grouped in Cluster 0 tend to have higher current prices, higher price change, higher cash ratio, higher net income, higher earnings per share and higher estimated shares outstanding. Moreover, companies that are grouped under Cluster 1 would have higher volatility, returns on equity, net cash flow, and P/E and P/B ratios.
  • As such, companies in Cluster 0 have higher stability in terms of their stock prices in the market, so they are much more appealing to any investor who likes to seek reliable returns over time. As for companies in Cluster 1, they are much more volatile, so investing in them would be very risky, but could potentially be highly rewarding. Thus, investors who prefer to stay safe and maintain steady returns, they should stick to companies as listed in Cluster 0. Investors, who can take on the risks to get higher yields, should choose companies in Cluster 1 (as sorted by the K-means clustering model).
